{
  "text": "The size of the hydrophobic segment determines both the morphology of the aggregates in aqueous solution (the hydrophobic fraction in total mass, f hydrophobic , of about 60%-70% forms polymersomes) and the mechanical characteristics of the membrane [CITATION_1] . Mechanical stability of polymersome membranes increases with hydrophobic thickness and further by crosslinking polymers [CITATION_2] . The elastic area modulus (K) of poly(ethylene oxide)-poly(dimethylsiloxane) (PEO-PDMS) graft polymer with 1.5 kDa of PDMS was reported to be ~93 mN/m with a critical area strain (\u03b1) of ~0.075 [CITATION_3] . The K values are similar to or a bit less than those of liposomes (60-300), but the \u03b1 values are higher than those of liposomes (<0.05) [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . The K depends on the interfacial tension, i.e., composition, of the membrane [CITATION_8] and the bending modulus is proportional to K\u00b7 h 2 , where h is membrane thickness [CITATION_9] .",
  "correct_citation": {
